description.narrative: (Moldova): To enable Moldova to better withstand economic pressures from Russia and rebuild a strong, market-driven economy, the High Value Agriculture Activity (HVAA) strengthens the agricultural sector and builds trading ties with non-CIS countries. The project works across agricultural value chains to improve productivity and quality to meet market demands, link producers and processors with international markets, bolster member-based organizations to be more competitive, and strengthen the workforce. HVAA will enhance the resilience of Moldovan HVA value chains by focusing on export market facilitation using digital platforms and building the capacity of key sectoral associations to provide market information and design export market development initiatives. Activities will include implementing e-commerce and online marketing tools for agribusinesses, as well as developing and disseminating online education platforms for associations and vocational schools. Furthermore, HVAA will assist associations and producers to improve market understanding and build market linkages, as well as develop online communication channels, promotions to increase domestic consumption, and building awareness of Moldovan products for exports. FY20 funds will expand the pool of Moldovan growers adopting international certifications, such as Global G.A.P, allowing them to access new high value markets in the EU and beyond and also reducing dependency on the Russian market. HVAA will forge stronger linkages between producers and processors, opening new marketing channels for small growers and ensuring Moldova has sufficient food supplies. HVAA makes Moldova more attractive for investment and provides U.S. businesses with new opportunities. The activity supports CAATSA Goal 8 (50 percent) and JRS Goal 2 Strengthen and Balance the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Relationship... .

Objectives for Moldova: The project aims to assist 600 enterprises in enhancing production capacities and the marketing and export of high value agricultural products; 280 agricultural entrepreneurs adopting advanced postharvest technologies; 3,500 farmers applying new varieties and modern technologies of cultivation of agricultural products; 5,000 farmers trained in advanced production and post-harvest technology
